Text.Value: I hope you've come to make a lodgement. A city-sized one.
I don't have your coin. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_2_463b0f43-5410-412d-aba3-875cf81c38ca])
What does the cult want with that much money?
In our hands, it keeps this city ticking over. Stock in merchants' stalls, food in hungry bellies.
Funny, that. I don't give a damn about him, but I care very much where the coin went.
I just need to find Minsc. I care nothing for coin.
Here's the coin that was taken. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
What was that about your guards turning cultist?
Eh, look, I just mean to say - we both want him caught. If you've got your sights set on the Stone Lord anyway...

EditorData.NodeContext: He accidentally referred to Jaheira as a crone and is backing off a little, doesn't want to piss her off

Text.Value: I see. Well. By all means... keep me up to date. If you do come back - feel free to bring that coin you took...?

EditorData.NodeContext: Scared shitless but pretending to be reasonably debating the point with Minsc. Last bit about gold is a last-ditch gambit

Text.Value: You can tell Nine-Fingers - this was not my fault. She swore that mimic could swallow a bloody owlbear.
I came to stop you and save Minsc. Seems there was no need.
But I need something back, understand? ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_2_463b0f43-5410-412d-aba3-875cf81c38ca])
Just tell me what happened.
Do it, then. Won't put bread on anyone's table, if that's what you actually care about.
On the one hand, you are clearly evil, and deserving of a mouthful of righteous knuckle.
You're a little late, master bandit.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry - not impressed by our boast of being a master thief

Text.Value: Aye, my own sword-arms. Loyal to the Guild, but more importantly - loyal to me.

EditorData.NodeContext: Referring to the guards who just turned on him - they were taken in by the cult (but in actual fact, tadpoled)

Text.Value: Try all of it. Every penny of civilian lodgings, anyway. Not like we'd lead him into the private vaults. But, still - lot of Baldurians waking up poor tomorrow.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'Not like we'd let him...' part is a snort of derision at the idea of letting anyone steal their wealthy customers gold.

Text.Value: I don't care about the coin. I just need to know where he went.
But on the other hand - the one in which Boo sits, and pleads your case - at the time of our last meeting, Minsc was the evil one.
The heist on Manycoins bank in Neverwinter. Ring a bell?
You lost innocent people's money. The Guild ought to swallow some of that cost.
Maybe you do. Gets me a beating, and gets you exactly nothing.
'Yes sir, Stone Lord, sir. Shall we open the account in your name, or the Absolute's? Just step this way to your special deposit box - don't mind the teeth.'

EditorData.NodeContext: Mock-polite and helpful tone, describing how he played along in an effort to trick the stone lord. 'Don't mind the teeth' is a reference the chest they tricked Minsc into - a mimic.

Text.Value: So. We are not agreed on whether we will return here and feed you to a mimic - yet.
Retrieve the coin, and I'll make sure you are well rewarded. There's treasures greater than gold.
HAH!

EditorData.NodeContext: Snort of pure derision - we just suggested he personally cover some of the bank's losses

Text.Value: With what he cleared from our vaults, he's got enough gold to make himself a lord in truth.
But that's why I pay my guards so well - to keep me well looked-after.
Feel free to poke around this place if it'll help you pick up the Stone Lord's scent. Me - I've got ledgers to amend.

EditorData.NodeContext: Closing the topic, wants to get back to business

Text.Value: On the one hand, you are clearly evil, and deserving of a mouthful of righteous knuckle.
Oh, enough. Should I wash the feet of every beggar down by the docks, too?

EditorData.NodeContext: Doesn't want to hear any more of our bleeding heart nonsense, relenting just to make us stop

Text.Value: Gratitude of the gold variety, I suppose you mean? Good luck with that.
You're missing your motley, jester. We softened our defences to lure that bastard in. Nine-Fingers wants the Stone Lord dead.
Say I find the money. What's to stop me keeping it for myself?
Wait - you're no Guild-sworn. Who are you?
Not for us, you understand. For the common Baldurian. Who knows what he's planning to do with it?

EditorData.NodeContext: Absolutely full of shit

Text.Value: Minsc has no use for such large numbers. As with my hamster, smaller would be better.
I'd listen to him. Before his hamster has to give him a head rub.
What he can do with that kind of coin... doesn't bear thinking about.
Hamster...? But - look, I can't. The losses -

EditorData.NodeContext: Confused, exasperated, but ultimately relenting

Text.Value: Compassion for your fellow folk? Or maybe just good sense - that much money only paints a target on your back.
The Stone Lord just cleared our vaults - and now he has enough gold to make himself a lord in truth.
Those conniving little shits. My own guards, turned cultist? I pay better than any bloody Absolute.
Here's the coin. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_2_463b0f43-5410-412d-aba3-875cf81c38ca])
Wait - you. What in Shar's shitting shadows have you come back for?

EditorData.NodeContext: Sudden shock, fear masked by anger - player is using Minsc to speak to Rakath. Last time they met, Minsc almost killed Rakath.

Text.Value: Never knew them to be god-botherers. But we've sent them to be with their precious Absolute now - good riddance.

EditorData.NodeContext: Referring to the guards who just turned on him - they were taken in by the cult (but in actual fact, tadpoled)

Text.Value: A lot of people will suffer. You can be the one who did that to them, or you can be the one who helped.
You have been the subject of many wrinkled brows between my hamster and I, Saer Banker-Beard.
But on the other hand - the one in which Boo sits, and pleads your case - at the time of our last meeting, Minsc was the evil one.
Security consultant. Your vaults leave a little to be desired.
Not my coin. That of every common mucker in Baldur's Gate.
Let's me and you make sure they don't all wake up as paupers tomorrow, hm?
So come back when you have it, aye?
Why the elaborate trap?
Fine. I'll pull in some debts with the other Guild kingpins - I can cover maybe half of what's lost.

EditorData.NodeContext: Frustrated sigh as you relent - you're being extorted and you have no choice.

Text.Value: Friend to the mad Rashemaar, are you? He calls himself the Stone Lord now.
A thief - one who could strip you of every copper if I so chose.
Maybe I'll just tell Nine-Fingers about your failure here instead.
Leave.
You're not going to have much of a head for numbers if I crack it open.
This should be the part where I reward you... but looks like someone's nicked my key. Eh... consider this your one-time permission to crack the vault open. But if anyone asks, I never said it.
No one mentioned he might have some old crone dropping in as backup.

EditorData.NodeContext: Back to annoyed and defensive voice

Text.Value: You think anyone told me? Nine-Fingers sent word the Stone Lord was going to try his luck on our vaults. So she told me to cooperate - lure him in.

EditorData.NodeContext: Shrugging, not being particularly helpful

Text.Value: Me too, I suppose, because I'm not even tempted to scam you. Take this vault key - you'll find something by way of thanks inside.
I... wish I could help you, Stone Lord. I really do. But it's just the economy, yeah?

EditorData.NodeContext: Wary, doesn't want to get beaten over it, but it's just not in him to bring the number down. He can't even explain it so just gestures vaguely at 'the economy'.

Text.Value: Saer Stone Lord. Minsc. Any... progress on that gold?

EditorData.NodeContext: Scared shitless but hoping against hope Minsc has returned the gold

Text.Value: I'm trying to hire you, and you're extorting me - with a dash of violence on top. Might be you have a future in the Guild.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dry, annoyed -

Text.Value: And not even a whisker light. Gods, you're a boring bastard. A beautiful bastard! Sir.

EditorData.NodeContext: Amazed we didn't steal anything, falling into patter, realising we're Minsc and scrambling to correct himself lamely

Text.Value: Or you can be the one to return all that money, and get a nice, shiny reward in return.
And you - you're no Guild-sworn. Who are you?

EditorData.NodeContext: Turning to player

Text.Value: You saw what he did to that mimic, aye? Would you take him head-on if you thought you could just play along instead?

EditorData.NodeContext: Won't have his plan questioned - it was better than a direct fight

Text.Value: Aye. The Head Banker was beaten to death by a mob, on the rumour she'd taken a cut from the robbers. You... wouldn't stoop to spreading rumours now, would you...?

EditorData.NodeContext: Warily recalling an old story he heard that we're using to threaten him.

Text.Value: And he wouldn't even know what to spend it on. It's the cult that needs that money - why?
These large numbers, they wrinkle Minsc's brow and bring a soreness to his skull. Make them smaller, please.

EditorData.NodeContext: Air of friendly threat. You're intimidating a corrupt banker to eat some of his own losses before you'll agree to retrieve his stolen coin.

Text.Value: I don't have your coin. ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
Crone...?
You have been the subject of many wrinkled brows between my hamster and I, Saer Banker-Beard.
I'm the heroic tale you'll tell your children. A touch of gratitude is in order.
The person who just saved your life. A little gratitude wouldn't go amiss.
So. We are not agreed on whether we will return here and feed you to a mimic - yet.
Our cunning trap just got flipped arse-ways up, is what. Nine-Fingers wants the Stone Lord dead.
Leave.
Good for you. I happen to care a very great deal.
Now, respectfully and all that bollocks - I asked who you are.

EditorData.NodeContext: Getting us back on track, not that respectfully at all

Text.Value: I see. Well. By all means... keep me up to date.
How much was taken?
As chairman of the Fellowship of Financiers, I can assure you we'd reward you well for the return of the coin he took.
Oh. You're serious. Maybe you don't have a head for accounting, but that's... not quite how the numbers work.

EditorData.NodeContext: Patronising

Text.Value: Now the guildmaster needn't skin me for a pair of boots. Though she still might like to.
And not even a whisker light. Gods, you're a boring bastard.

Synopsis: The Head Banker is grateful to be saved and can reveal some details about what happened in the Counting House
